04690nam a22006375i 9780674269583DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742695837 a10.4159/97806742695832doi  a(DE-B1597)590531  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aNA1540 7aARC0050002bisacsh1 aSteinhardt, Nancy Shatzman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Borders of Chinese Architecture /cNancy Shatzman Steinhardt. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Borders Problem -- t1. Chinese Architecture before China -- t2. Han -- t3. Architecture before Reunification -- t4. Seeing the Sixth Century as the Seventh and Eighth -- t5. Tang Internationalism -- t6. Defining Chinese Architecture and Borders during Liao -- t7. Western Xia, Song, Japan, Jin -- t8. A Revisionist History of Yuan Architecture -- t9. Ming -- t10. The Long Eighteenth Century -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn internationally acclaimed expert explains why Chinese-style architecture has remained so consistent for two thousand years, no matter where it is built. For the last two millennia, an overwhelming number of Chinese buildings have been elevated on platforms, supported by pillars, and covered by ceramic-tile roofs. Less obvious features, like the brackets connecting the pillars to roof frames, also have been remarkably constant. What makes the shared features more significant, however, is that they are present in Buddhist, Daoist, Confucian, and Islamic milieus; residential, funerary, and garden structures; in Japan, Korea, Mongolia, and elsewhere. How did Chinese-style architecture maintain such standardization for so long, even beyond China’s borders? Nancy Shatzman Steinhardt examines the essential features of Chinese architecture and its global transmission and translation from the predynastic age to the eighteenth century. Across myriad political, social, and cultural contexts within China and throughout East Asia, certain design and construction principles endured. Builders never abandoned perishable wood in favor of more permanent building materials, even though Chinese engineers knew how to make brick and stone structures in the last millennium BCE. Chinese architecture the world over is also distinctive in that it was invariably accomplished by anonymous craftsmen. And Chinese buildings held consistently to the plan of the four-sided enclosure, which both afforded privacy and differentiated sacred interior space from an exterior understood as the sphere of profane activity. Finally, Chinese-style buildings have always and everywhere been organized along straight lines. Taking note of these and other fascinating uniformities, The Borders of Chinese Architecture offers an accessible and authoritative overview of a tradition studiously preserved across time and space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067426958340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269583/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE 